# Plan: Add Pagination to GET /users

## Context
The `GET /users` endpoint currently returns all 15 users as a flat JSON array. The tests (already written) expect a paginated response with a `data` array and a `pagination` metadata object. The implementation needs to catch up to the tests.

## Scope
**One file to change**: `/src/routes.ts`

No new files, no new utilities, no changes to `data.ts`, `types.ts`, or `app.ts`.

---

## Implementation

### File: `/src/routes.ts`

Replace the current `GET /users` handler:

```typescript
// BEFORE
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});
```

With this paginated version:

```typescript
// AFTER
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page = parseInt(req.query.page as string) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string) || 10;
  const total = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const startIndex = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data = users.slice(startIndex, startIndex + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

### Key logic decisions
| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| Default `page` | `1` (via `\|\| 1` fallback) |
| Default `limit` | `10` (via `\|\| 10` fallback) |
| Out-of-range page | `Array.prototype.slice` returns `[]` naturally when `startIndex >= array.length` — no special casing needed |
| `totalPages` | `Math.ceil(total / limit)` — e.g. 15 users / 10 = `2` pages; 15 / 5 = `3` pages |

---

## How the tests will pass

| Test | Expected | Logic |
|---|---|---|
| Default (no params) | page=1, limit=10, data.length=10, total=15, totalPages=2 | `slice(0, 10)` → 10 users |
| `?page=2&limit=10` | page=2, data.length=5 | `slice(10, 20)` → users 11-15 (5 users) |
| `?limit=5` | data.length=5, totalPages=3 | `ceil(15/5)=3`, `slice(0,5)` |
| `?page=100` | status 200, data=[] | `slice(990, 1000)` → `[]` |
| `GET /users/:id` | unchanged | not modified |

---

## Verification
Run the test suite:
```bash
npm test
